00:03:04.450 --> 00:03:05.343
- Steve?

00:03:06.550 --> 00:03:09.663
- Yeah, because our government
is way, way, way too big.

00:03:10.830 --> 00:03:13.043
- Well, let me elaborate.

00:03:13.043 --> 00:03:15.940
(audience laughs)

00:03:15.940 --> 00:03:20.940
What we have here is, the
term crony capitalism, Steve,

00:03:21.240 --> 00:03:24.670
is one that I keep on hearing,
many people call themselves

00:03:24.670 --> 00:03:27.960
conservative Republicans use, and I agree.

00:03:27.960 --> 00:03:31.680
I have seen really over the last 50 years,

00:03:31.680 --> 00:03:35.610
my first job was in Robert
F. Kennedy's Senate office.

00:03:35.610 --> 00:03:37.120
I was an intern in 1967.

00:03:38.980 --> 00:03:42.270
And I've seen just this
tide of money coming into

00:03:42.270 --> 00:03:45.590
Washington, now the interesting
question and I think here

00:03:45.590 --> 00:03:48.470
is where we may disagree
is cause and effect.

00:03:48.470 --> 00:03:51.830
And I have seen the
tide of money coming in

00:03:51.830 --> 00:03:54.910
mostly from big corporations
and from Wall Street

00:03:56.326 --> 00:03:58.460
and from wealthy individuals
in order to influence

00:03:58.460 --> 00:04:02.420
government, and Steve, I
don't know whether you see it

00:04:02.420 --> 00:04:06.500
that way, or whether you
see government being large

00:04:06.500 --> 00:04:09.330
and as it gets large,
there's more money coming in

00:04:09.330 --> 00:04:13.020
to influence it, but there's
no question that money

00:04:13.020 --> 00:04:15.780
has taken over much of our policy making

00:04:15.780 --> 00:04:19.630
and I hope you agree with me
and that's a real problem.

00:04:19.630 --> 00:04:22.641
- So look, I mean, by
the way, let me just say,

00:04:22.641 --> 00:04:25.030
right from the start that
I want to thank my friends

00:04:25.030 --> 00:04:27.500
at Young America's
Foundation for sponsoring me

00:04:27.500 --> 00:04:29.763
to come here, so thank you, yeah for that.

00:04:30.910 --> 00:04:32.910
I think the causality
goes both directions.

00:04:32.910 --> 00:04:35.790
I mean, I think there's a
lot of naivete on the left.

00:04:35.790 --> 00:04:37.593
People say, oh my God, there's
so much money in politics,

00:04:37.593 --> 00:04:39.500
they're spending so
much money on lobbying,

00:04:39.500 --> 00:04:41.640
they're spending so
much money on campaigns,

00:04:41.640 --> 00:04:44.630
but folks, we have a four
trillion dollar budget.

00:04:44.630 --> 00:04:46.050
Four trillion dollars.

00:04:46.050 --> 00:04:49.070
Is it a surprise that
companies and special interests

00:04:49.070 --> 00:04:52.990
and whether it's the gun lobby
or this lobby or that lobby

00:04:52.990 --> 00:04:55.380
is going to spend a lot of money, in fact,

00:04:55.380 --> 00:04:57.520
I'm surprised that the
lobbyists aren't spending

00:04:57.520 --> 00:05:00.730
even more money trying to elect candidates

00:05:00.730 --> 00:05:04.410
and trying to influence
Congress because when I first

00:05:04.410 --> 00:05:07.200
came to Washington, you
mentioned that you worked for

00:05:07.200 --> 00:05:09.520
Robert F Kennedy, when
I came to Washington,

00:05:09.520 --> 00:05:13.130
I'm a little younger than you are in 1983,

00:05:13.130 --> 00:05:15.230
the federal budget was

00:05:16.932 --> 00:05:19.060
at that time, I'll never forget
this 'cause I was working

00:05:19.060 --> 00:05:21.720
in the Reagan administration at that time

00:05:21.720 --> 00:05:23.330
and I was working for Jim Miller, who was

00:05:23.330 --> 00:05:25.550
the budget director, '84, '85

00:05:25.550 --> 00:05:28.550
and we introduced the first
one trillion dollar budget

00:05:28.550 --> 00:05:30.243
in American history, we
were very proud of that

00:05:30.243 --> 00:05:34.310
as Reaganites and I'll just
tell you one really interesting

00:05:34.310 --> 00:05:35.470
quick story about that.

00:05:35.470 --> 00:05:39.180
So Jim Miller was supposed
to go on the Today Show

00:05:39.180 --> 00:05:42.840
which was the show with Katie
Couric and he couldn't do it

00:05:42.840 --> 00:05:45.200
that morning because he
got sick and he called me

00:05:45.200 --> 00:05:48.420
and he said, Steve, can you
go on Katie Couric's show

00:05:48.420 --> 00:05:51.010
and defend the president's budget?

00:05:51.010 --> 00:05:52.860
And I spent literally the next two nights

00:05:52.860 --> 00:05:56.900
just completely cramming
every statistic I knew

00:05:56.900 --> 00:05:59.448
in the budget, I knew what the budget was

00:05:59.448 --> 00:06:02.130
for the army, you know, the
Department of Agriculture,

00:06:02.130 --> 00:06:04.190
World Series, whatever
it was, so I was ready

00:06:04.190 --> 00:06:06.850
for any question Katie
Couric might ask me.

00:06:06.850 --> 00:06:09.740
And Katie, the lights
come on, cameras rolling,

00:06:09.740 --> 00:06:11.070
Katie Couric kind of
growls at me, she says,

00:06:11.070 --> 00:06:14.540
Mr. Moore, I see that
Ronald Reagan is introducing

00:06:14.540 --> 00:06:18.160
the first one trillion dollar
budget in American history.

00:06:18.160 --> 00:06:21.030
Says, my first question
for you this morning is

00:06:21.908 --> 00:06:23.553
how many zeroes are there in a trillion?

00:06:23.553 --> 00:06:24.580
(men laugh)

00:06:24.580 --> 00:06:26.691
You know, I just melted down.

00:06:26.691 --> 00:06:29.740
It was the worst interview of my life,

00:06:29.740 --> 00:06:32.430
but my point is, it was a
trillion dollar budget back then.

00:06:32.430 --> 00:06:35.240
By the way, there are
12 zeroes in a trillion,

00:06:35.240 --> 00:06:36.970
I know that now by heart.

00:06:36.970 --> 00:06:39.180
But now we're at four
trillion and even adjusting

00:06:39.180 --> 00:06:40.870
for inflation, we've doubled it.

00:06:40.870 --> 00:06:42.810
We're spending way too much money.

00:06:42.810 --> 00:06:45.270
We have so much crap in the tax code.

00:06:45.270 --> 00:06:48.170
One of the things we tried
to do in this tax bill.

00:06:48.170 --> 00:06:51.210
We didn't, we succeeded a
little bit but not much,

00:06:51.210 --> 00:06:54.220
is get rid of all the
junk in the tax system.

00:06:54.220 --> 00:06:57.040
One of the things that I
think Bob and I might agree on

00:06:57.040 --> 00:06:59.570
is the idea of let's get rid
of all the special interest

00:06:59.570 --> 00:07:03.610
loopholes in the tax system
for all of the special lobbies

00:07:03.610 --> 00:07:06.290
and get the rates down and that would be

00:07:06.290 --> 00:07:08.970
an efficient tax system, so less spending

00:07:08.970 --> 00:07:11.580
and a simpler tax system
I think would reduce

00:07:11.580 --> 00:07:12.600
the influence of the lobbyists.

00:07:12.600 --> 00:07:14.270
Now why would you be against that?

00:07:14.270 --> 00:07:17.003
- I'm not, I'm not, again,
it's cause and effect.

00:07:17.003 --> 00:07:20.801
What I've witnessed, and
this is certainly the case

00:07:20.801 --> 00:07:25.390
at least since the mid '80s,
is that the lobbyists come in

00:07:25.390 --> 00:07:28.340
and they want exemptions,
they want loopholes,

00:07:28.340 --> 00:07:31.380
they want everything
because they want to justify

00:07:31.380 --> 00:07:34.050
to their industry and to
their trade association

00:07:34.050 --> 00:07:36.870
and to others that they've,
basically they're worth

00:07:36.870 --> 00:07:38.496
all of the money that they're charging

00:07:38.496 --> 00:07:43.496
and that set of loopholes
and that set of exemptions

00:07:44.240 --> 00:07:46.110
makes everything more complicated.

00:07:46.110 --> 00:07:47.720
It makes the tax code more complicated,

00:07:47.720 --> 00:07:50.068
it makes the enforcement more complicated

00:07:50.068 --> 00:07:53.790
and also it results in less
revenue for the government

00:07:53.790 --> 00:07:55.630
so it drives up deficits.

00:07:55.630 --> 00:08:00.630
There is almost no way to
stop all of this, short of--

00:08:01.240 --> 00:08:04.540
- A flat tax, oh, sorry. (laughs)

00:08:04.540 --> 00:08:05.870
- No.

00:08:05.870 --> 00:08:06.790
(audience laughs)

00:08:06.790 --> 00:08:09.530
Short of major campaign finance reform

00:08:09.530 --> 00:08:14.530
and full disclosure of who's
actually contributing what

00:08:14.990 --> 00:08:18.480
to every campaign or
against every campaign.

00:08:18.480 --> 00:08:21.405
And public financing and a
lot of things that can be done

00:08:21.405 --> 00:08:25.300
even with Citizens United
and Steve, I think you and I

00:08:25.300 --> 00:08:27.620
would agree on much of that.

00:08:27.620 --> 00:08:30.858
- So let me just give one
example of something I worked

00:08:30.858 --> 00:08:34.150
this past, you know, six
to nine months trying

00:08:34.150 --> 00:08:36.690
to get rid of, a special interest
provision in the tax code,

00:08:36.690 --> 00:08:38.960
something probably a
lot of you in this room,

00:08:38.960 --> 00:08:41.830
I'm just guessing probably
favor, which is, you know,

00:08:41.830 --> 00:08:44.659
we have these massive
giveaways in the tax code.

00:08:44.659 --> 00:08:46.650
To the wind and solar industry.

00:08:46.650 --> 00:08:49.660
We pay them money to
produce energy because

00:08:49.660 --> 00:08:53.800
they're so inefficient relative
to coal and natural gas

00:08:53.800 --> 00:08:57.550
and the industry even admitted,
the wind industry said

00:08:58.519 --> 00:09:01.068
there would be no wind
industry in America today

00:09:01.068 --> 00:09:02.640
were it not for these tax
subsidies and guess what,

00:09:02.640 --> 00:09:04.340
we couldn't get rid of
'em because a lot of your

00:09:04.340 --> 00:09:08.700
Democratic friends, you know,
said they couldn't possibly

00:09:08.700 --> 00:09:10.690
support that and some Republicans as well.

00:09:10.690 --> 00:09:13.500
My point is, too oftentimes
liberals say, well,

00:09:13.500 --> 00:09:14.980
we're against the special interests,

00:09:14.980 --> 00:09:17.947
we're against this or that,
but when it's their special

00:09:17.947 --> 00:09:19.360
interest, they're in favor of it.

00:09:19.360 --> 00:09:22.441
- Well what about, but oil
and gas, Steve, get so much

00:09:22.441 --> 00:09:23.441
subsidies.
- Get rid of those

00:09:23.441 --> 00:09:24.710
subsidies too.
- Let's get rid of

00:09:24.710 --> 00:09:27.540
all of those subsidies,
but I don't understand

00:09:27.540 --> 00:09:31.430
how the carried interest
subsidy interest loophole.

00:09:31.430 --> 00:09:33.022
- I wanted to get rid of that too.

00:09:33.022 --> 00:09:35.380
- Well, wait a minute, how did
it survive, because everybody

00:09:35.380 --> 00:09:36.657
- Because there were a lot--

00:09:36.657 --> 00:09:37.821
- Everybody, including the President--

00:09:37.821 --> 00:09:40.480
- There were about eight
private equity billionaires,

00:09:40.480 --> 00:09:41.870
I mean, it sort of makes your point.

00:09:41.870 --> 00:09:43.600
Who give a lot of money
to the Republican party

00:09:43.600 --> 00:09:46.620
who said we can't support this
bill if you get rid of it.

00:09:46.620 --> 00:09:50.030
I fought it, you know,
and in the end of the day,

00:09:50.030 --> 00:09:53.110
that private interest loophole
is still in the tax system.

00:09:53.110 --> 00:09:56.493
I'm embarrassed by that, but
I'm gonna make a second run

00:09:56.493 --> 00:09:57.326
at that, I promise you guys.
- I'm embarrassed by it too

00:09:57.326 --> 00:09:58.730
and I'm embarrassed by a lot of things,

00:09:58.730 --> 00:10:01.830
but we can't get rid of it
and all of these loopholes

00:10:01.830 --> 00:10:06.059
and all of this corporate
welfare until we get some control

00:10:06.059 --> 00:10:09.080
on campaign finance and
you would, it sounds like

00:10:09.080 --> 00:10:10.080
you're agreeing with me on this.

00:10:10.080 --> 00:10:11.590
- You know, I...

00:10:11.590 --> 00:10:14.430
What I'm for is people
disclosing what they're giving.

00:10:14.430 --> 00:10:17.030
I think we should have open,
if you're gonna give money

00:10:17.030 --> 00:10:20.160
it should all be disclosed
and let people out there see.

00:10:20.160 --> 00:10:21.693
- Full disclosure.

00:10:21.693 --> 00:10:23.080
(men laugh)

