Three of the five wealthiest
counties in America

00:11:50.310 --> 00:11:53.150
are in and around Washington DC.

00:11:53.150 --> 00:11:54.930
Now how did that happen?

00:11:54.930 --> 00:11:56.310
Because you know what folks?

00:11:56.310 --> 00:11:58.950
We don't produce anything.

00:11:58.950 --> 00:12:03.030
All we produce is lawyers,
lobbyists, special interests,

00:12:03.030 --> 00:12:05.550
politicians, rules and
regulations, and we're getting rich

00:12:05.550 --> 00:12:07.130
off it, and you know
what, the American people

00:12:07.130 --> 00:12:09.130
are getting pretty upset about it, so.

00:12:09.130 --> 00:12:11.708
- Well, let me just, I
don't want to go too long

00:12:11.708 --> 00:12:14.250
on this, because we have agreement here.

00:12:14.250 --> 00:12:19.250
In 1976, 3% of retiring
members of Congress

00:12:19.736 --> 00:12:22.380
became lobbyists, 3%.

00:12:22.380 --> 00:12:24.760
Today, 49%.
- Pathetic.

00:12:24.760 --> 00:12:27.110
- Of retiring members of
Congress, from both parties,

00:12:27.110 --> 00:12:30.100
become lobbyists, and I think that's--

00:12:30.100 --> 00:12:31.210
- I'm surprised it's that low.

00:12:31.210 --> 00:12:33.939
- And I think it's a testament
to the amount of money

00:12:33.939 --> 00:12:36.660
that is circulating in Washington

00:12:36.660 --> 00:12:39.884
and that's got to stop, so
we have an agreement, good.

00:12:39.884 --> 00:12:42.398
- Let's move on to tariffs,
so Bob, you were an early

00:12:42.398 --> 00:12:45.660
opponent of the Transpacific Partnership,

00:12:45.660 --> 00:12:48.290
and I think Steve has
got some criticisms of it

00:12:48.290 --> 00:12:51.260
but was basically a
proponent of free trade

00:12:51.260 --> 00:12:53.800
and of the Transpacific
Partnership, although

00:12:53.800 --> 00:12:55.920
you can speak for
yourself, but tell me why

00:12:55.920 --> 00:12:58.970
you were opposed to the
Transpacific Partnership

00:12:58.970 --> 00:13:00.954
and does that mean you're
in league with Donald Trump?

00:13:00.954 --> 00:13:03.240
(audience laughs)

00:13:03.240 --> 00:13:07.680
- Well, last question
first, no, but I didn't like

00:13:08.670 --> 00:13:11.150
the dispute mechanisms, in
fact, there was a similar

00:13:11.150 --> 00:13:13.960
dispute mechanism in a
much smaller form in NAFTA,

00:13:13.960 --> 00:13:16.670
the North American Free
Trade Act, but actually

00:13:16.670 --> 00:13:19.525
under TPP, you have a much larger version

00:13:19.525 --> 00:13:23.200
and that dispute mechanism
is between any corporation,

00:13:23.200 --> 00:13:26.950
for example, that feels
that for some reason

00:13:26.950 --> 00:13:31.110
a member state, a member
country, to the TPP

00:13:31.110 --> 00:13:34.560
has discriminated against
them or there's a non tariff

00:13:34.560 --> 00:13:37.480
barrier, health, safety,
environmental regulation,

00:13:37.480 --> 00:13:42.480
labor regulation, whatever,
and that dispute can be

00:13:42.650 --> 00:13:47.413
under the TPP, could be
dealt with by arbitrators and

00:13:49.210 --> 00:13:52.040
the arbitrators are not
necessarily selected

00:13:52.040 --> 00:13:57.040
by any member country but
the net result is that

00:13:57.100 --> 00:14:01.860
anybody who has a grievance
and could be rewarded damages

00:14:01.860 --> 00:14:04.170
from those health, safety or
environmental regulations.

00:14:04.170 --> 00:14:08.843
If you follow my argument,
that means that the TPP

00:14:09.680 --> 00:14:14.680
could discourage any member
country from generating

00:14:15.510 --> 00:14:20.510
any protections for the
health, safety or environment

00:14:20.560 --> 00:14:25.274
or labor and that to
me is not only an issue

00:14:25.274 --> 00:14:29.300
of sovereignty but it also
is an issue of just politics.

00:14:29.300 --> 00:14:33.150
It means it would be harder,
that much harder actually

00:14:33.150 --> 00:14:36.203
to protect members of that society.

00:14:37.175 --> 00:14:38.270
- In general, though,
are you for free trade?

00:14:38.270 --> 00:14:40.209
Do you think that's a good idea?

00:14:40.209 --> 00:14:42.012
As a principle?
- In general, I,

00:14:42.012 --> 00:14:44.221
in general as a principle,
of course, I think free trade

00:14:44.221 --> 00:14:47.560
is a good idea, but see, this
is the interesting issue,

00:14:47.560 --> 00:14:52.560
Henry, we have debated free
trade for years and I've been

00:14:54.370 --> 00:14:57.270
on the side of well, stronger
environmental and labor

00:14:57.270 --> 00:14:59.990
protections, Steve, you've
been on the side of free trade.

00:14:59.990 --> 00:15:03.610
We've debated deficits,
I've been on the side of

00:15:03.610 --> 00:15:06.810
well, deficits may not
always be a problem.

00:15:06.810 --> 00:15:09.920
You and other conservatives
have been on the side of

00:15:09.920 --> 00:15:11.830
we really do need to control deficits.

00:15:11.830 --> 00:15:15.010
We've debated states' rights
and I've been on the side of

00:15:15.010 --> 00:15:17.420
federal government does
really need to preempt states

00:15:17.420 --> 00:15:19.260
and you and other conservatives
have been on the side

00:15:19.260 --> 00:15:22.740
of states' rights, we debated Russia

00:15:22.740 --> 00:15:25.700
and I've been saying, you
know, we really shouldn't be

00:15:25.700 --> 00:15:28.080
so hard on Russia, and you
have been on the side of

00:15:28.080 --> 00:15:29.450
we have to be more aggressive on Russia.

00:15:29.450 --> 00:15:32.645
Every one of these issues, we
have completely flipped around

00:15:32.645 --> 00:15:36.963
under Donald Trump, every one
of them is now the opposite.

00:15:37.820 --> 00:15:38.773
- So I mean, look.

00:15:39.740 --> 00:15:41.950
I always say about Donald
Trump, you know, 'cause I've

00:15:41.950 --> 00:15:44.170
gotten to know him very
well and I admire a lot

00:15:44.170 --> 00:15:46.852
about Donald Trump, but look,
there is a good and a bad

00:15:46.852 --> 00:15:49.050
and an ugly, when it comes to Donald Trump

00:15:49.050 --> 00:15:51.369
and every morning...

00:15:51.369 --> 00:15:52.300
- [Robert] Do you want
to assign percentages

00:15:52.300 --> 00:15:53.925
to each of those?

00:15:53.925 --> 00:15:55.146
(audience laughs)

00:15:55.146 --> 00:15:55.979
- Every morning, this is
not being taped, right?

00:15:55.979 --> 00:15:57.660
But no, every morning
when I say my prayers,

00:15:57.660 --> 00:16:00.820
I say please God, let the
angel on his shoulder,

00:16:00.820 --> 00:16:03.660
not the devil on his
other shoulder, prevail.

00:16:03.660 --> 00:16:06.890
So when it comes to issues
like Russia, you know,

00:16:06.890 --> 00:16:10.740
I don't understand this
dalliance with even what he said

00:16:10.740 --> 00:16:13.410
today, congratulating
Putin on the election.

00:16:13.410 --> 00:16:16.100
Why would you congratulate
a guy who rakes elections

00:16:16.100 --> 00:16:17.242
on winning an election?

00:16:17.242 --> 00:16:20.280
So you're right about
that, now on this issue.

00:16:20.280 --> 00:16:22.584
- I do have a theory to explain that.

00:16:22.584 --> 00:16:24.980
(audience laughs)

00:16:24.980 --> 00:16:27.530
- I'm not so sure I want to hear it.

00:16:27.530 --> 00:16:29.930
On this trade thing, I
mean, this is getting to be

00:16:29.930 --> 00:16:33.280
a very complicated issue,
we're gonna see in the next

00:16:33.280 --> 00:16:38.280
week or so a major call for
a major tariff against China.

00:16:38.830 --> 00:16:41.530
I have to confess, I'm
not an expert on the TPP

00:16:41.530 --> 00:16:42.870
so I'm not gonna really get into that.

00:16:42.870 --> 00:16:45.540
I will say this, that
I learned my economics

00:16:45.540 --> 00:16:47.890
from Milt and Friedman,
who I think are two

00:16:47.890 --> 00:16:51.280
great economists, and
they always talk about

00:16:51.280 --> 00:16:53.844
the four pillars of
prosperity, and those pillars,

00:16:53.844 --> 00:16:56.690
and I think they're just
important to write down.

00:16:56.690 --> 00:16:58.893
Sound money, I think we all agree on that,

00:17:00.057 --> 00:17:02.057
a sound currency that retains its value.

00:17:03.000 --> 00:17:05.370
Second of all you need free trade.

00:17:05.370 --> 00:17:08.100
Third of all, you need a
light hand of regulation

00:17:08.100 --> 00:17:10.750
and fourth a good tax
system, and I still believe

00:17:10.750 --> 00:17:12.830
that to this day, that if you
get those four things right,

00:17:12.830 --> 00:17:15.870
you're gonna have a prosperous economy.

00:17:15.870 --> 00:17:19.120
Trump challenges the conventional
wisdom of conservatives

00:17:19.120 --> 00:17:21.490
on a lot of these things,
there's no question about it.

00:17:21.490 --> 00:17:25.774
On trade, we can get into
this into a bigger way.

00:17:25.774 --> 00:17:28.895
I think trade, I mean, I think Trump,

00:17:28.895 --> 00:17:32.650
there's new, what I call
a Trump trade doctrine

00:17:32.650 --> 00:17:35.880
and what that doctrine is...

00:17:35.880 --> 00:17:39.630
Using, look, the United States is the hub

00:17:39.630 --> 00:17:41.940
of the global economy, right,
and every other country

00:17:41.940 --> 00:17:45.358
is a spoke and what
Trump is basically saying

00:17:45.358 --> 00:17:47.382
and I've talked to him about this is

00:17:47.382 --> 00:17:50.360
whether it's China, whether it's Japan

00:17:50.360 --> 00:17:53.520
or whether it's Korea
or whether it's Mexico,

00:17:53.520 --> 00:17:55.552
they need us more than we need them

00:17:55.552 --> 00:17:59.151
so let's say we had, God
forbid, a trade war with China.

00:17:59.151 --> 00:18:01.350
What would it mean for the United States?

00:18:01.350 --> 00:18:04.240
Well, it'd mean when you go
to Wal-mart, you might have

00:18:04.240 --> 00:18:07.360
to pay 10 cents more for
toothpaste or you might have

00:18:07.360 --> 00:18:10.780
to pay $29 more for a
cellphone 'cause a lot of these

00:18:10.780 --> 00:18:15.240
phones are made in China,
if China can't sell to us

00:18:15.240 --> 00:18:17.560
they go into a recession,
right, and I think

00:18:17.560 --> 00:18:21.330
what Trump is basically
trying to do here is

00:18:21.330 --> 00:18:24.190
use that leverage and that's
why, remember the other day

00:18:24.190 --> 00:18:26.860
when he said, we can win a trade
war or something like that,

00:18:26.860 --> 00:18:29.750
I mean, with Trump you have
to kind of read through

00:18:29.750 --> 00:18:31.710
what he's saying, what he meant to say is,

00:18:31.710 --> 00:18:34.680
we have a strategic advantage
over them because if it gets

00:18:34.680 --> 00:18:37.245
to that point, they have
more to lose than we do

00:18:37.245 --> 00:18:38.940
and they're gonna blink
first, I think that's what,

00:18:38.940 --> 00:18:41.610
and by the way, you
can disagree with Trump

00:18:41.610 --> 00:18:44.500
on the policy, right, I mean,
you can say this is stupid,

00:18:44.500 --> 00:18:46.393
like, I thought the steel
tariffs were stupid.

00:18:46.393 --> 00:18:47.406
- The steel?

00:18:47.406 --> 00:18:50.690
- The steel tariffs I
thought were a bad idea

00:18:50.690 --> 00:18:53.420
because all you're doing is
raising the price of steel.

00:18:53.420 --> 00:18:55.560
I told the president,
I said, you're not even

00:18:55.560 --> 00:18:59.280
gonna create factory jobs
here because for every one

00:18:59.280 --> 00:19:01.630
steel worker, we have 50
workers in manufacturing

00:19:01.630 --> 00:19:04.500
that use steel, now our steel's
gonna be 20% more expensive

00:19:04.500 --> 00:19:06.830
than the steel, so it doesn't
even work in that respect,

00:19:06.830 --> 00:19:10.041
but I will say this, you
know, and you know this

00:19:10.041 --> 00:19:11.280
because you've done
this too, I mean, I went

00:19:11.280 --> 00:19:16.050
with Donald Trump to
Pennsylvania, Ohio, Michigan,

00:19:16.050 --> 00:19:19.080
West Virginia, Iowa, those
blue states that went red

00:19:19.080 --> 00:19:24.080
and I would say that if Trump
had taken a conventional

00:19:24.080 --> 00:19:27.040
Republican position on trade,
Hillary Clinton would be

00:19:27.040 --> 00:19:30.701
president today, so this is
a challenge for those of us

00:19:30.701 --> 00:19:33.250
who believe in free trade, right?

00:19:33.250 --> 00:19:36.680
We haven't convinced the
American people that free trade

00:19:36.680 --> 00:19:37.513
is good.

00:19:37.513 --> 00:19:39.360
- But don't you think
a lot of that has to do

00:19:39.360 --> 00:19:42.600
with the failure of both
parties to deal with

00:19:42.600 --> 00:19:44.530
the consequences of technology?

00:19:44.530 --> 00:19:45.500
- That's true too.

00:19:45.500 --> 00:19:46.640
- Which is actually having
a much bigger effect.

00:19:46.640 --> 00:19:48.750
- I totally agree with you.
- On jobs.

00:19:48.750 --> 00:19:51.320
- By the way, let me just, on steel,

00:19:51.320 --> 00:19:53.170
the reason we're losing steel jobs is not

00:19:53.170 --> 00:19:55.356
because of trade, it's
because if you go, when I was

00:19:55.356 --> 00:19:59.390
12 years old, I grew up in
Chicago, my parents took me

00:19:59.390 --> 00:20:01.683
to a steel mill in Michigan,
I mean, that was like

00:20:01.683 --> 00:20:05.020
a 19th century sweatshop
with thousands of workers

00:20:05.020 --> 00:20:07.250
carrying around heavy
beams, I mean, truly,

00:20:07.250 --> 00:20:09.840
drudgery work, you go into--
- And a lot of injuries.

00:20:09.840 --> 00:20:10.830
A lot of injuries.

00:20:10.830 --> 00:20:14.440
- Yeah, today steel mills
are people walking around,

00:20:14.440 --> 00:20:17.040
it's all being done robotics,
Trump is wrong on this.

00:20:17.040 --> 00:20:19.230
We're not losing steel
jobs because of trade.

00:20:19.230 --> 00:20:21.660
It's because of, and by the
way, that's gonna continue.

00:20:21.660 --> 00:20:23.630
10 years from now there
won't be any steel jobs,

00:20:23.630 --> 00:20:25.410
probably, right, because of technology.

00:20:25.410 --> 00:20:30.220
- Right, but back, if it's
true that both parties

00:20:30.220 --> 00:20:33.600
have failed to deal with
the quote unquote losers,

00:20:33.600 --> 00:20:36.800
the people who are losing
their, what had been

00:20:36.800 --> 00:20:40.040
middle class jobs because
of first technology,

00:20:40.040 --> 00:20:45.040
secondly globalization, then
isn't the debate over tariffs

00:20:46.530 --> 00:20:49.200
sort of beside the point,
I mean, shouldn't we say,

00:20:49.200 --> 00:20:52.790
let's not, let's not try to
protect industries with tariffs.

00:20:52.790 --> 00:20:56.010
Let's try to make it easier
for people to move from

00:20:56.010 --> 00:20:58.447
job to job and get better
and better and better jobs

00:20:58.447 --> 00:21:00.950
with better education,
better job training,

00:21:00.950 --> 00:21:03.692
more of a re-employment assistance?

00:21:03.692 --> 00:21:04.900
- Yeah, yes.

00:21:04.900 --> 00:21:07.004
- Put that down, that's another issue.

00:21:07.004 --> 00:21:09.490
- (laughs) No, I mean,
you're absolutely right.

00:21:09.490 --> 00:21:12.720
I mean, now look, the problem
is, like Hillary would go

00:21:12.720 --> 00:21:15.155
to these towns in West
Virginia, we went to these

00:21:15.155 --> 00:21:19.560
coal towns, and you know,
these places have been just

00:21:19.560 --> 00:21:21.910
decimated, in no small
part, in my opinion,

00:21:21.910 --> 00:21:23.970
because of Obama
regulations that just killed

00:21:23.970 --> 00:21:26.840
the coal industry, now,
there's an example though, Bob,

00:21:26.840 --> 00:21:30.770
where Trump has gotten rid of
a lot of those regulations,

00:21:30.770 --> 00:21:32.840
and guess what, the coal industry is back.

00:21:32.840 --> 00:21:36.390
We're, and my point is,
though, Hillary went and said

00:21:36.390 --> 00:21:38.473
exactly what you said, oh,
you can do something else.

00:21:38.473 --> 00:21:40.547
We'll retrain you for this or that.

00:21:40.547 --> 00:21:42.510
- No, no, politically, that's--

00:21:42.510 --> 00:21:44.330
- It's her thing to
tell a guy who's worked

00:21:44.330 --> 00:21:47.319
in a coal mine for 25 years, oh, you know,

00:21:47.319 --> 00:21:48.592
you're not gonna be
able to do that anymore.

00:21:48.592 --> 00:21:49.593
You're gonna do something else,

00:21:49.593 --> 00:21:50.900
but I'll give you another statistic.

00:21:50.900 --> 00:21:55.900
One out of 11 males in
America today is hired,

00:21:56.180 --> 00:21:59.360
what they do for a living
is drive a vehicle.

00:21:59.360 --> 00:22:01.690
Now how many of those jobs
do you think will still exist

00:22:01.690 --> 00:22:02.590
12 years from now?

00:22:02.590 --> 00:22:04.800
- Four and a half million
are gonna be eliminated.

00:22:04.800 --> 00:22:08.053
- Yeah, exactly, so this
adjustment is happening,

00:22:09.249 --> 00:22:11.972
it's the issue of our time,
frankly, I mean, folks,

00:22:11.972 --> 00:22:13.040
this technological boom that's coming,

00:22:13.040 --> 00:22:15.170
whether it's artificial intelligence,

00:22:15.170 --> 00:22:18.740
whether it's robotics, whether
it's the driverless cars,

00:22:18.740 --> 00:22:22.610
they are gonna change life in
this country and on the planet

00:22:22.610 --> 00:22:25.430
in ways that nobody is looking
at and make these other

00:22:25.430 --> 00:22:26.370
issues small.

00:22:26.370 --> 00:22:28.880
- But so what does government
do in these situations?

00:22:28.880 --> 00:22:31.470
You want the government
smaller, but it seems to me

00:22:31.470 --> 00:22:33.700
that if we're going to help
people who lose their jobs

00:22:33.700 --> 00:22:36.310
in these instances and
there are no other jobs,

00:22:36.310 --> 00:22:38.020
what do we say to these people?

00:22:38.020 --> 00:22:41.640
- Don't we have to have
stronger safety nets?

00:22:41.640 --> 00:22:44.580
Don't we have to have a
universal basic income?

00:22:44.580 --> 00:22:47.590
Don't we have to have a larger
earned income tax credit?

00:22:47.590 --> 00:22:49.540
Don't we have to have
a re-employment system

00:22:49.540 --> 00:22:52.140
that provides education and job retraining

00:22:52.140 --> 00:22:53.850
that is really useful to these people?

00:22:53.850 --> 00:22:56.123
In other words, politically,
both of us agree

00:22:56.123 --> 00:22:59.100
it's not possible to say to these people,

00:22:59.100 --> 00:23:00.560
we're gonna get you another job

00:23:00.560 --> 00:23:02.240
or you're going to get another job,

00:23:02.240 --> 00:23:07.240
but don't we have to be serious
about making it possible

00:23:08.450 --> 00:23:09.860
for these people?

00:23:09.860 --> 00:23:12.824
- Well, look, I'm not one who believes

00:23:12.824 --> 00:23:14.760
that this is the end of
work and end of jobs.

00:23:14.760 --> 00:23:18.497
I mean, there will be jobs
in the year 2025 and 2030

00:23:19.707 --> 00:23:21.527
and 2035, there'll probably be more jobs

00:23:21.527 --> 00:23:23.530
than there are today, but
they'll be different kinds

00:23:23.530 --> 00:23:26.510
of jobs, and we're not, I
mean, my point is, look,

00:23:26.510 --> 00:23:29.400
the kinds of things you're
talking about small potatoes

00:23:29.400 --> 00:23:30.433
in the grand scheme of things.

00:23:30.433 --> 00:23:34.586
What we have to do is get the
next generation of workers

00:23:34.586 --> 00:23:37.460
ready for the, you know, look,

00:23:37.460 --> 00:23:39.290
you've got to have a skill.

00:23:39.290 --> 00:23:43.310
Right now today if you have
any useful skill out there

00:23:43.310 --> 00:23:46.290
whatsoever, you can find a job in 24 hours

00:23:46.290 --> 00:23:47.930
and there's five million
more jobs out there than

00:23:47.930 --> 00:23:50.350
there are people to fill them,
so what are we talking about?

00:23:50.350 --> 00:23:52.810
There's not a shortage of...

00:23:52.810 --> 00:23:54.427
Jobs right now, there's
a shortage of people

00:23:54.427 --> 00:23:56.290
who are trained to do the jobs.

00:23:56.290 --> 00:23:59.680
If you're a mechanic,
if you're a carpenter,

00:23:59.680 --> 00:24:02.900
if you're an engineer,
if you know anything

00:24:02.900 --> 00:24:05.110
about computers, you can
find those jobs out there.

00:24:05.110 --> 00:24:07.860
The problem is and I'll say
this about this university

00:24:07.860 --> 00:24:09.800
but every university, I mean,
we're graduating with kids

00:24:09.800 --> 00:24:12.790
with psychology degrees and
political science degrees

00:24:12.790 --> 00:24:15.440
and frankly, there's not
a big demand for those.

00:24:15.440 --> 00:24:17.704
- Well, just for the record,
there's a great demand

00:24:17.704 --> 00:24:21.480
for UC Berkeley graduates,
they do very well.

00:24:21.480 --> 00:24:22.690
(audience applauds)

00:24:22.690 --> 00:24:24.640
They really, really do.
- That's why you're here.

00:24:24.640 --> 00:24:27.050
- And this university
is extremely successful

00:24:27.050 --> 00:24:30.540
at educating people to go on
to make very, very good money.

00:24:30.540 --> 00:24:31.779
I'd be happy to show you the data.

00:24:31.779 --> 00:24:33.345
Sorry.

00:24:33.345 --> 00:24:35.783
(audience laughs)

00:24:35.783 --> 00:24:36.616
(audience applauds)

00:24:36.616 --> 00:24:40.029
- But I think, Henry, that
Steve is absolutely right

00:24:40.029 --> 00:24:41.972
that the issue--
- You write that down.

00:24:41.972 --> 00:24:46.090
- The issue in the future
is not the number of jobs.

00:24:46.090 --> 00:24:49.831
The number of jobs really does
reflect macroeconomic factors

00:24:49.831 --> 00:24:54.540
stimulating demand adequately,
it's the quality of the jobs.

00:24:54.540 --> 00:24:58.202
It's what the jobs pay and
that's what I worry about.

00:24:58.202 --> 00:24:59.770
- Well, the higher paying
jobs, not lower paying jobs.

00:24:59.770 --> 00:25:01.850
- Well, we're not seeing that trend.

00:25:01.850 --> 00:25:03.533
In fact, for the last 40
years, Steve, you and I

00:25:03.533 --> 00:25:07.950
have been talking about this,
median wages have been stuck.

00:25:07.950 --> 00:25:09.000
There's been wage stagnation.

00:25:09.000 --> 00:25:10.986
- Not the last, no, no,
that's where you and I

00:25:10.986 --> 00:25:15.986
part company, for the last 15
years they have been stuck,

00:25:16.420 --> 00:25:19.696
but we saw, now, it depends
on what kind of compensation,

00:25:19.696 --> 00:25:22.470
but if you look at just
compensation to workers

00:25:22.470 --> 00:25:24.450
when you include benefits
and things like that,

00:25:24.450 --> 00:25:28.890
in the 80s, we had a big boom
in middle class, you know,

00:25:28.890 --> 00:25:33.020
compensation and Laura
Tyson is here, what you guys

00:25:33.020 --> 00:25:36.610
did in the 90s, that was a great
period for the middle class

00:25:36.610 --> 00:25:40.350
I would argue the 80s and
90s were great periods of

00:25:41.914 --> 00:25:42.747
economic mobility for people.

00:25:42.747 --> 00:25:45.090
Now it stalled in the last
15 years 'cause I think

00:25:45.090 --> 00:25:47.117
we've done a lot of stupid
things that haven't been

00:25:47.117 --> 00:25:50.120
good policy, but this
idea that, I mean, look,

00:25:50.120 --> 00:25:52.690
I reject this idea which
you say all the time.

00:25:52.690 --> 00:25:54.880
Workers are not as well
off today as they were 40

00:25:54.880 --> 00:25:57.855
years ago, I mean, does
anybody really believe that?

00:25:57.855 --> 00:25:59.696
I mean, come on.
(audience says "yes")

00:25:59.696 --> 00:26:03.022
No, 40 years, we didn't
have all these things,

00:26:03.022 --> 00:26:04.153
we didn't have the
computers, we didn't have

00:26:04.153 --> 00:26:07.040
the technology, we didn't
have the big screen TVs,

00:26:07.040 --> 00:26:08.660
we didn't have the medicines
that we have today,

00:26:08.660 --> 00:26:11.433
the world is so much,
would anybody really rather

00:26:11.433 --> 00:26:15.060
have been alive 40 or
50 years ago than today?

00:26:15.060 --> 00:26:16.505
Come on.

00:26:16.505 --> 00:26:19.810
- Here's the thing, you
know, 50 years ago, even 40

00:26:19.810 --> 00:26:23.200
years ago, we had something
called labor unions,

00:26:23.200 --> 00:26:25.985
which gave workers a lot
of bargaining leverage

00:26:25.985 --> 00:26:30.438
and right now today, we have fewer than 7%

00:26:30.438 --> 00:26:32.440
in the private sector are unionized

00:26:32.440 --> 00:26:35.380
and that shows, there's
an absolute correlation

00:26:35.380 --> 00:26:40.030
between the median wage, the
decline of the bottom 60%,

00:26:40.030 --> 00:26:42.825
particularly men, and the
decline of unionization

00:26:42.825 --> 00:26:45.245
and Steve, you and I can
really bore everybody

00:26:45.245 --> 00:26:48.470
with a data fight over
whether or not adjusted

00:26:48.470 --> 00:26:52.960
for inflation today's wages
for the bottom 60%, 70 or 80%

00:26:52.960 --> 00:26:57.950
of males are better than they
were, 40 or 50 years ago.

00:26:57.950 --> 00:27:00.450
I don't think they are,
but we can debate that.

00:27:00.450 --> 00:27:03.670
I think the point is that
quality jobs are really

00:27:03.670 --> 00:27:05.731
critically important
and a lot of the anger

00:27:05.731 --> 00:27:10.731
that I saw in 2015 and 2016,
going into the election,

00:27:11.440 --> 00:27:14.193
one of the reasons I
think that Bernie Sanders

00:27:14.193 --> 00:27:17.040
and Donald Trump did as
well as they both did,

00:27:17.040 --> 00:27:20.640
surprising everybody, was
both of them responded

00:27:20.640 --> 00:27:23.350
in very different ways to
the anger that so many people

00:27:23.350 --> 00:27:26.320
had about a system, a
political economic system,

00:27:26.320 --> 00:27:28.490
that was not responding.
- I agree with that.

00:27:28.490 --> 00:27:30.651
I think that's true.

00:27:30.651 --> 00:27:32.750
People are, but I would
only make the point

00:27:32.750 --> 00:27:35.180
that I think it was political,
economic and cultural.

00:27:35.180 --> 00:27:38.140
I mean, people, you know,
look, what Hillary said

00:27:38.140 --> 00:27:41.000
the other day, you know,
was the way I think

00:27:41.000 --> 00:27:43.310
a lot of us conservatives
think that liberals

00:27:43.310 --> 00:27:46.100
think about them, you know,
there was a view of these,

00:27:46.100 --> 00:27:48.560
'cause I talked to a lot
of these Trump voters,

00:27:48.560 --> 00:27:51.270
these middle class voters, and
they were basically feeling

00:27:51.270 --> 00:27:53.880
like number one, they
were afraid to speak out

00:27:53.880 --> 00:27:55.270
because of political correctness.

00:27:55.270 --> 00:27:57.540
One thing that Trump did
I thought masterfully

00:27:57.540 --> 00:28:01.630
was just, you know, put aside the rules

00:28:01.630 --> 00:28:03.240
of political correctness and violate them

00:28:03.240 --> 00:28:05.121
and people would say,
finally, somebody's saying

00:28:05.121 --> 00:28:08.580
the kinds of things that we
wanted to say for 15 years

00:28:08.580 --> 00:28:11.450
but we get shouted down every
time we want to see them.

00:28:11.450 --> 00:28:13.440
These kinds of speech
codes on college campus.

00:28:13.440 --> 00:28:17.300
I hope you don't have speech
codes here in Berkeley.

00:28:17.300 --> 00:28:19.420
I mean, universities should
be places where you have

00:28:19.420 --> 00:28:21.460
open expression, that's
why I so much appreciate

00:28:21.460 --> 00:28:23.032
the opportunity to come here and talk,

00:28:23.032 --> 00:28:26.030
but too often, conservatives feel like

00:28:26.030 --> 00:28:28.700
we're just being
smothered by liberal rules

00:28:28.700 --> 00:28:31.210
and that kind of thing, and so

00:28:31.210 --> 00:28:33.090
I think it was cultural as well.

00:28:33.090 --> 00:28:34.890
- Well, let me just say for the record,

00:28:34.890 --> 00:28:37.090
I know you don't mean this, but I think

00:28:37.090 --> 00:28:40.320
that Donald Trump has legitimized hate.

00:28:40.320 --> 00:28:43.070
(audience applauds)

00:28:43.070 --> 00:28:46.610
- I think he's legitimized
a sense of hopelessness

00:28:46.610 --> 00:28:49.260
of people and a sense that
their voices aren't being heard.

00:28:49.260 --> 00:28:52.350
- Well, the other thing that
you said about Donald Trump

00:28:52.350 --> 00:28:54.890
saying that he was going to
take on the swamp in Washington,

00:28:54.890 --> 00:28:58.120
he did say that, but the
swamp is deeper and bigger

00:28:58.120 --> 00:29:00.570
and broader and fatter and
there are more swamp creatures

00:29:00.570 --> 00:29:03.202
than I ever saw in Washington ever before.

00:29:03.202 --> 00:29:04.210
(audience applauds)

00:29:04.210 --> 00:29:08.403
I want to, I don't want,
this is not fair to Steve.

00:29:08.403 --> 00:29:11.900
This is Berkeley and if you
applaud what I'm saying.

00:29:11.900 --> 00:29:15.180
This, I mean, I really
appreciate you being here.

00:29:15.180 --> 00:29:19.270
I asked you to get a visa
to come into Berkeley.

00:29:19.270 --> 00:29:21.364
- No, but look, on this
trade issue, I really want

00:29:21.364 --> 00:29:23.230
your kind of reaction, I want to throw out

00:29:23.230 --> 00:29:25.460
a kind of hypothesis on this
and I want your reaction.

00:29:25.460 --> 00:29:26.950
I asked Laura about this earlier.

00:29:26.950 --> 00:29:30.210
Trump is basically gonna
say, we're gonna put a 30%

00:29:30.210 --> 00:29:32.790
tariff on Chinese goods
and that's coming I think

00:29:32.790 --> 00:29:35.520
in the next week or two, and
that's gonna be a big boom.

00:29:35.520 --> 00:29:37.280
I mean, the world is
gonna react in a big way.

00:29:37.280 --> 00:29:41.060
That's gonna get Beijing's
attention in a big way and,

00:29:41.060 --> 00:29:43.570
you know, I am a free trader
and I want you to react

00:29:43.570 --> 00:29:46.810
to this, but look, China,
the report just came out

00:29:46.810 --> 00:29:51.080
a few weeks ago, the Chinese
are stealing $500 billion

00:29:51.080 --> 00:29:52.700
of our technologies every year.

00:29:52.700 --> 00:29:55.720
A lot of that technology
and that knowhow and patents

00:29:55.720 --> 00:29:57.890
and the copyrights and
the computer software,

00:29:57.890 --> 00:30:01.350
that's made right here, right, in Berkeley

00:30:01.350 --> 00:30:04.238
and the Bay Area and Silicon
Valley, they're stealing it.

00:30:04.238 --> 00:30:07.860
We also know that they're
building up their military

00:30:07.860 --> 00:30:10.450
in China, we also know that
the reason this lunatic

00:30:10.450 --> 00:30:12.896
in North Korea has a nuclear
bomb is because China

00:30:12.896 --> 00:30:16.080
enabled that to happen and you know what?

00:30:16.080 --> 00:30:19.170
I'm with Trump on this,
I think it is time we get

00:30:19.170 --> 00:30:22.293
really tough with China and
basically say, you're not

00:30:22.293 --> 00:30:26.210
gonna have access to American
markets until you behave

00:30:26.210 --> 00:30:28.770
like civilized people,
and you're not doing that.

00:30:28.770 --> 00:30:30.843
You're cheating and you
can't have free trade

00:30:30.843 --> 00:30:32.900
with a country that's
cheating and stealing.

00:30:32.900 --> 00:30:37.890
- Well, I want to say first
of all that China is a rogue

00:30:37.890 --> 00:30:40.790
in terms of trade, I
agree with that entirely,

00:30:40.790 --> 00:30:43.710
and if you're incorporating
in terms of your definition

00:30:43.710 --> 00:30:46.650
of trade, intellectual property
theft, I agree with that

00:30:46.650 --> 00:30:48.674
as well.
- What do we do about it?

00:30:48.674 --> 00:30:51.130
- That's the question,
what do we do about it,

00:30:51.130 --> 00:30:54.730
because I'm afraid that a 30%
tariff or any major tariff

00:30:54.730 --> 00:30:57.250
on Chinese goods coming
to this country is going

00:30:57.250 --> 00:31:00.776
to shoot us in the foot
more than it hurts China.

00:31:00.776 --> 00:31:01.810
- Wow, how could that be?

00:31:01.810 --> 00:31:04.660
- Well, it could be
because China is a large

00:31:04.660 --> 00:31:07.860
and growing economy and
it is very self sufficient

00:31:07.860 --> 00:31:08.700
in many ways.

00:31:08.700 --> 00:31:11.137
- But they need access to our markets.

00:31:11.137 --> 00:31:13.800
- And also its sphere
of influence is growing.

00:31:13.800 --> 00:31:16.980
The United States right
now doesn't play the role

00:31:16.980 --> 00:31:20.160
of world leadership that
we played in the past

00:31:20.160 --> 00:31:23.740
and I think that when
we are in that position,

00:31:23.740 --> 00:31:26.170
China is going to continue
to trade with the rest

00:31:26.170 --> 00:31:29.719
of the world, with Europe,
with Canada, with every major

00:31:29.719 --> 00:31:33.294
nation, we are going to be left out.

00:31:33.294 --> 00:31:35.937
- I don't believe that, I
just don't believe that.

00:31:35.937 --> 00:31:39.150
The rebuilding of our
economy that's happening,

00:31:39.150 --> 00:31:42.180
in no small part because of
Trump policies on regulation--

00:31:42.180 --> 00:31:43.900
- What do you expect
China will be able to do,

00:31:43.900 --> 00:31:46.170
because for example, one
of the things you want them

00:31:46.170 --> 00:31:49.990
to do is to open up to us,
but that might be even more

00:31:49.990 --> 00:31:53.170
frightening than a recession
to them because that might

00:31:53.170 --> 00:31:57.700
lead to Americans being
much more in the economy,

00:31:57.700 --> 00:32:01.010
maybe a Facebook run by Facebook
in China that really isn't

00:32:02.106 --> 00:32:03.689
censored and so on and so forth,

00:32:03.689 --> 00:32:04.522
that's really scary to the Chinese.

00:32:04.522 --> 00:32:06.280
Do you think that's really
feasible, that something

00:32:06.280 --> 00:32:07.860
like that's gonna happen?

00:32:07.860 --> 00:32:10.662
- I'm not sure I'm following,
I'm not sure I understand.

00:32:10.662 --> 00:32:11.495
- Well, I'm saying that
if we started to have

00:32:11.495 --> 00:32:14.720
more opening to China, that
means we have, for example,

00:32:14.720 --> 00:32:16.830
perhaps a Facebook we're running in China

00:32:16.830 --> 00:32:19.210
that's uncensored because I
think that's the kind of thing

00:32:19.210 --> 00:32:22.500
you're asking for, real
free trade, but if you have

00:32:22.500 --> 00:32:25.670
an uncensored Facebook in
China, the regime is not

00:32:25.670 --> 00:32:28.450
gonna be happy with what's
gonna be on that Facebook.

00:32:28.450 --> 00:32:31.790
- Of course, I mean, look,
this is an oppressive regime.

00:32:31.790 --> 00:32:35.427
They're tyrants, they are not, they...

00:32:35.427 --> 00:32:38.070
Look, the leader there just made himself

00:32:38.070 --> 00:32:40.330
the president for life, they're
not gonna have elections.

00:32:40.330 --> 00:32:41.800
- So what do you expect him to do,

00:32:41.800 --> 00:32:44.650
are there things they can do
that will satisfy Mr. Trump

00:32:44.650 --> 00:32:49.253
and us and that allow us
to not impose a 30% tariff?

00:32:49.253 --> 00:32:51.000
- So he can basically say a couple things.

00:32:51.000 --> 00:32:54.030
Help with disarming North
Korea, right, how many of you

00:32:54.030 --> 00:32:56.500
are for that, don't you want
to have North Korea not have

00:32:56.500 --> 00:32:58.900
a nuclear bomb, I mean,
we have the leverage

00:32:58.900 --> 00:33:03.030
to force them to do it,
maybe we do, maybe we don't,

00:33:03.030 --> 00:33:07.540
but we should try, number
two, they have to start,

00:33:07.540 --> 00:33:10.220
I mean, this is a point
that Laura Tyson was making

00:33:10.220 --> 00:33:12.130
earlier and I think it
makes a lot of sense.

00:33:12.130 --> 00:33:14.000
We should...

00:33:14.000 --> 00:33:16.249
Get them to buy more of our
stuff, whether it's our weed

00:33:16.249 --> 00:33:19.074
or our cotton or whether it's
our copper or our computers

00:33:19.074 --> 00:33:22.470
and actually pay us for
it and that's the kind of

00:33:22.470 --> 00:33:24.760
trade deal that needs
to be made with China.

00:33:24.760 --> 00:33:28.200
- That is precisely the
question, how do we get them?

00:33:28.200 --> 00:33:30.121
- Because if they don't, then
they're gonna be severely

00:33:30.121 --> 00:33:32.630
penalized, and this is
where I disagree with you.

00:33:32.630 --> 00:33:36.650
They can't function as an economy in 2018

00:33:36.650 --> 00:33:39.583
if they can't sell to
America's four trillion dollar

00:33:39.583 --> 00:33:41.514
consumer economy.

00:33:41.514 --> 00:33:42.920
- Well, but there are
two parts to your thesis.

00:33:42.920 --> 00:33:44.860
One is that they're gonna
be hurt more than we are

00:33:44.860 --> 00:33:48.450
gonna be hurt and secondly
that by doing that,

00:33:48.450 --> 00:33:51.100
the outcome is going to
be we get more leverage

00:33:51.100 --> 00:33:52.760
and that down the road
they're going to change

00:33:52.760 --> 00:33:53.903
their policies.
- They're gonna blink.

00:33:53.903 --> 00:33:55.378
- And they're gonna blink.
- You don't think they will.

00:33:55.378 --> 00:33:58.230
- I think it's a dangerous,
dangerous game to play

00:33:58.230 --> 00:34:01.369
and we could end up easily worse off.

00:34:01.369 --> 00:34:03.399
Now a lot of--
- So what's the alternative?

00:34:03.399 --> 00:34:06.208
- A lot of our exports,
you know, there may be

00:34:06.208 --> 00:34:10.840
an alternative in terms of
using the rest of the world.

00:34:10.840 --> 00:34:14.452
The rest of the world has
an interest in an open

00:34:14.452 --> 00:34:16.350
trading system.
- Sure, absolutely.

00:34:16.350 --> 00:34:19.310
- The rest of the world also
has an interest in rules

00:34:19.310 --> 00:34:22.268
that everybody plays by
that are neutral rules

00:34:22.268 --> 00:34:25.900
and why can't we, I mean,
we were already making

00:34:25.900 --> 00:34:29.680
some progress, I mean, the
WTO, I think was a very good

00:34:29.680 --> 00:34:34.510
idea, the World Trade
Organization, and Chinese ascension

00:34:34.510 --> 00:34:37.980
to the WTO, I thought
opened the way, if it were

00:34:37.980 --> 00:34:39.360
correctly used.
- They don't,

00:34:39.360 --> 00:34:41.400
they violate every WTO rule.

00:34:41.400 --> 00:34:43.280
- I'm gonna end this because
I think what we need to do

00:34:43.280 --> 00:34:45.840
is get a panel of Chinese
experts in here to say

00:34:45.840 --> 00:34:47.800
what's the likelihood they
will blink or won't blink.

00:34:47.800 --> 00:34:50.770
Because, you folks know
a lot about economics

00:34:50.770 --> 00:34:54.030
but I don't think China is
your greatest expertise.

00:34:54.030 --> 00:34:57.045
So let's go to another area
where I think you will have

00:34:57.045 --> 00:35:00.320
expertise, and that's the 2017 tax bill.

00:35:00.320 --> 00:35:02.660
You've already said, Steve,
that you think that it did

00:35:02.660 --> 00:35:05.996
good things and simplifying
the tax code in some ways

00:35:05.996 --> 00:35:10.025
and also providing tax breaks
that will help the economy.

00:35:10.025 --> 00:35:12.953
Bob, do you think that 2017
tax bill was a good tax bill

00:35:12.953 --> 00:35:17.470
and that it will really
actually be equitable for people

00:35:17.470 --> 00:35:19.980
and second of all that it
will stimulate the economy?

00:35:19.980 --> 00:35:20.813
- No.

00:35:21.716 --> 00:35:24.120
- Explain. (laughs)

00:35:24.120 --> 00:35:26.140
- You know, number one,
I think it's exacerbating

00:35:26.140 --> 00:35:29.710
already inequality, number
two, most of the profits,

00:35:29.710 --> 00:35:32.780
that extra profits that
corporations have got,

00:35:32.780 --> 00:35:35.410
corporations are using to buy
back their shares of stock.

00:35:35.410 --> 00:35:40.120
They are not using them to
invest or to increase wages

00:35:40.120 --> 00:35:44.210
of average workers, number
three, I think that it's going

00:35:44.210 --> 00:35:48.930
to exacerbate our deficit and
our national debt problems.

00:35:48.930 --> 00:35:52.810
Now I'm not a huge worrier
about the deficit or the debt

00:35:52.810 --> 00:35:54.430
but generally speaking they aren't

00:35:54.430 --> 00:35:55.654
going in the right direction

00:35:55.654 --> 00:35:58.810
and number four, politically, it sets up

00:35:58.810 --> 00:36:01.249
the Republicans and the
Trump administration

00:36:01.249 --> 00:36:05.086
for beginning to say, well,
we can't afford you name it.

00:36:05.086 --> 00:36:09.136
Medicare, Medicaid, Social
Security, it's kind of

00:36:09.136 --> 00:36:11.960
the starve the beast that we saw beginning

00:36:11.960 --> 00:36:14.163
under the Reagan administration,
so for those four reasons

00:36:14.163 --> 00:36:19.163
I think this was a terrible
idea and to add insult to injury

00:36:19.302 --> 00:36:23.095
I hear Larry Kudlow and his new boss

00:36:23.095 --> 00:36:27.139
are talking about a second
tax cut, is that right?

