- There's some talk about
that, so let me kind of explain

00:36:30.401 --> 00:36:33.023
very briefly what we did and why we did it

00:36:33.023 --> 00:36:34.940
because I think it's kind
of important for people

00:36:34.940 --> 00:36:38.205
to understand the thinking behind the plan

00:36:38.205 --> 00:36:41.750
and so Larry and I sat down
with Trump two years ago,

00:36:41.750 --> 00:36:44.930
walked him through this, he
got it pretty straightforwardly

00:36:44.930 --> 00:36:48.140
and I think, you know, you all will too.

00:36:48.140 --> 00:36:50.960
First of all, the heart
of the plan, the gemstone

00:36:50.960 --> 00:36:54.779
of the plan was to get our
business tax rates down.

00:36:54.779 --> 00:36:57.180
What we've been talking
about for the last 20 minutes

00:36:57.180 --> 00:36:59.980
is we're living in a
global economy, the genie

00:36:59.980 --> 00:37:03.000
is out of the bottle, it's
not being stuffed back in.

00:37:03.000 --> 00:37:05.400
You all aren't gonna just be
competing here in California

00:37:05.400 --> 00:37:07.570
against people in Tennessee
and Texas and Florida.

00:37:07.570 --> 00:37:09.540
You're gonna be competing
against people in Beijing

00:37:09.540 --> 00:37:12.560
and Germany and France
and Spain and Australia.

00:37:12.560 --> 00:37:15.670
We've got to get competitive
and we had a tax system,

00:37:15.670 --> 00:37:17.890
frankly, Bob, when it came
to the way we were taxing

00:37:17.890 --> 00:37:20.180
our businesses, you couldn't
have come up with anything

00:37:20.180 --> 00:37:23.790
stupider, you know, we had
the highest statutory rate

00:37:23.790 --> 00:37:27.730
in the world, so we were
at 40% when you count state

00:37:27.730 --> 00:37:31.890
and local taxes and the rest
of the world, which by the way,

00:37:31.890 --> 00:37:35.036
25 years ago was at 40%,
kept cutting and cutting

00:37:35.036 --> 00:37:36.900
and cutting and cutting and cutting.

00:37:36.900 --> 00:37:39.710
So much so that the rest of the
world was down to about 20%.

00:37:39.710 --> 00:37:42.400
We're at 40, ladies and
gentlemen, if you care about

00:37:42.400 --> 00:37:44.834
America, you care about
American workers and American

00:37:44.834 --> 00:37:46.950
companies, and you want
us to be number one,

00:37:46.950 --> 00:37:50.220
that doesn't work, it doesn't
work for us to be at 40,

00:37:50.220 --> 00:37:52.573
and them to be at 20, I called
this a headstart program

00:37:52.573 --> 00:37:55.420
for every country that
we're competing with.

00:37:55.420 --> 00:37:56.980
Why would we want to do that?

00:37:56.980 --> 00:38:00.050
So we basically said to Trump,
let's get that corporate rate

00:38:00.050 --> 00:38:02.436
down, you know, he wanted
15%, this is an area

00:38:02.436 --> 00:38:04.600
where he's a master negotiator.

00:38:04.600 --> 00:38:08.080
He stuck with 15% throughout
and that's how we got 21.

00:38:08.080 --> 00:38:10.420
If he had said 20, we would
have ended up with 25.

00:38:10.420 --> 00:38:12.250
We're right back in the game right now.

00:38:12.250 --> 00:38:15.030
All of a sudden, the reason
I think you're so wrong

00:38:15.030 --> 00:38:17.350
about the impact of this in
just the first three months

00:38:17.350 --> 00:38:19.910
and we're just sucking
capital now back into

00:38:19.910 --> 00:38:21.920
the United States in a huge way, I mean,

00:38:21.920 --> 00:38:24.650
the biggest economic news
story, ladies and gentlemen

00:38:24.650 --> 00:38:28.210
of the last three years,
was the Apple story.

00:38:28.210 --> 00:38:32.660
I mean, this is gigantic,
Apple is bringing 300 billion,

00:38:32.660 --> 00:38:37.180
not 300 million, $300 billion
back to the United States

00:38:37.180 --> 00:38:39.110
and they're gonna invest
it here, they're building

00:38:39.110 --> 00:38:41.940
a new plant with 25,000 workers, I mean,

00:38:41.940 --> 00:38:45.060
this is a big deal, and those
are gonna be good paying jobs.

00:38:45.060 --> 00:38:47.620
Now look, some of that money
will probably be paid off

00:38:47.620 --> 00:38:51.560
in dividends or buying up
shares of their own shares,

00:38:51.560 --> 00:38:53.800
by the way, why does a
company buy its own shares?

00:38:53.800 --> 00:38:56.480
Because it wants to increase
the value of the share, right?

00:38:56.480 --> 00:38:58.610
And we have 100 million
shareholders in this country,

00:38:58.610 --> 00:39:00.310
they're all gonna benefit from this too.

00:39:00.310 --> 00:39:03.010
So that's been a huge
benefit, we've already had

00:39:03.010 --> 00:39:06.260
five million American workers,
the vast majority of them

00:39:06.260 --> 00:39:09.580
in the middle class, who've
gotten bonuses, pay raises

00:39:09.580 --> 00:39:12.230
and increases in benefits,
I mean, the other day

00:39:12.230 --> 00:39:13.830
I'm walking down the
street, I was in Dallas,

00:39:13.830 --> 00:39:16.334
this Guatemalan woman
comes up to me, she says,

00:39:16.334 --> 00:39:17.607
are you the guy on CNN
who talks about economics?

00:39:17.607 --> 00:39:19.990
She said thank you for the tax cut.

00:39:19.990 --> 00:39:23.820
I just got a $1500 bonus from my employer.

00:39:23.820 --> 00:39:28.230
Now to Nancy Pelosi, $1500 may be crumbs,

00:39:28.230 --> 00:39:30.520
but you know what if you're
making $40,000 a year,

00:39:30.520 --> 00:39:33.100
a $1500 bonus is pretty significant.

00:39:33.100 --> 00:39:36.386
So this is going to help in
my opinion, Robert Reich,

00:39:36.386 --> 00:39:39.127
middle class workers as
we get more jobs here,

00:39:39.127 --> 00:39:41.870
we get more productive,
businesses invest here,

00:39:41.870 --> 00:39:43.580
that was the whole philosophy behind it.

00:39:43.580 --> 00:39:46.220
It was not and I'll repeat this 100 times.

00:39:46.220 --> 00:39:48.990
It was not because we wanted
rich people to make more money

00:39:48.990 --> 00:39:51.273
but here's a statistic for
you all to think about.

00:39:51.273 --> 00:39:54.350
When you talk about the top
1%, you know, the people

00:39:54.350 --> 00:39:56.880
who you say have all the
money, but what do those people

00:39:56.880 --> 00:39:58.090
do for a living?

00:39:58.090 --> 00:40:01.482
2/3 of them own, operate and
invest in small businesses

00:40:01.482 --> 00:40:04.630
and you can't have jobs without employers

00:40:04.630 --> 00:40:06.590
and that's what the whole thing was about,

00:40:06.590 --> 00:40:08.970
is getting money to the businesses

00:40:08.970 --> 00:40:10.980
so they can invest it in America.

00:40:10.980 --> 00:40:12.970
- Bob, I'm gonna give you a
second, I just want to say

00:40:12.970 --> 00:40:16.360
there's cards on your chairs
and if you want to write out

00:40:16.360 --> 00:40:19.800
a question please do so, and
then there will be people

00:40:19.800 --> 00:40:22.500
coming by to pick them up, and Bob Reich.

00:40:22.500 --> 00:40:24.086
- Well, for example.

00:40:24.086 --> 00:40:28.326
You can't have and businesses
are not going to invest

00:40:28.326 --> 00:40:33.100
without customers and one of
the biggest problems we have

00:40:33.100 --> 00:40:36.610
and businesses face as well
is a shrinking middle class.

00:40:36.610 --> 00:40:39.020
I mean, with so much of
the income and wealth

00:40:39.020 --> 00:40:41.178
in this country going
to the top, you know,

00:40:41.178 --> 00:40:44.700
wealthy people spend a
very small percentage of

00:40:44.700 --> 00:40:47.188
their income and certainly their wealth--

00:40:47.188 --> 00:40:48.287
- [Steve] They're investing
it in the business.

00:40:48.287 --> 00:40:50.260
- But they're not
investing, that's the point.

00:40:50.260 --> 00:40:53.230
- They're saving, what
are they doing with it?

00:40:53.230 --> 00:40:54.486
- Steve, you're saying
that they're buying back

00:40:54.486 --> 00:40:55.570
their shares of stock and
when you say that's great

00:40:55.570 --> 00:40:57.290
for everybody, that's not the case.

00:40:57.290 --> 00:40:59.928
I mean, the top 1% of
Americans owns 40% of the total

00:40:59.928 --> 00:41:04.309
stock market, the top 10% own
80% of the total stock market.

00:41:04.309 --> 00:41:06.000
- Well, where do you think
the California teachers

00:41:06.000 --> 00:41:08.717
pension fund is invested, all
of this money is invested--

00:41:08.717 --> 00:41:13.717
- But that is the reality,
that the top 10% own 80%--

00:41:14.430 --> 00:41:16.850
- Well, that's a terrible
thing, we should let people

00:41:16.850 --> 00:41:18.610
put their Social Security
money in the stock market

00:41:18.610 --> 00:41:19.547
so everybody owns stock.

00:41:19.547 --> 00:41:23.433
- But Steve, Steve, the
reality is, the reality is

00:41:23.433 --> 00:41:28.433
that taking all of this tax
money, these major tax cuts

00:41:29.960 --> 00:41:32.680
and giving it to corporations
in terms of increasing

00:41:32.680 --> 00:41:35.430
profits and then turning
around and buying back

00:41:35.430 --> 00:41:38.720
their shares and making
the wealthy even wealthier,

00:41:38.720 --> 00:41:41.330
that does not do anything
about the underlying problem

00:41:41.330 --> 00:41:43.699
of stagnant wages and widening inequality.

00:41:43.699 --> 00:41:48.577
Besides that, besides that,
there is kind of an underlying

00:41:48.577 --> 00:41:51.100
philosophical difference, and
you and I have been around

00:41:51.100 --> 00:41:53.877
this, you know, we've debated
this for 15 or 20 years

00:41:53.877 --> 00:41:58.540
about whether trickle down
economics actually works.

00:41:58.540 --> 00:42:02.810
And whether there is any
empirical data to support.

00:42:02.810 --> 00:42:04.140
- Which there is.
- Trickle down economics.

00:42:04.140 --> 00:42:05.580
Which there isn't.

00:42:05.580 --> 00:42:07.660
- (laughs) I mean, we
look at the same body.

00:42:07.660 --> 00:42:10.700
I mean, the three most
prosperous periods, you know,

00:42:10.700 --> 00:42:14.720
for the last 100 years, were
the 20s, when Calvin Coolidge

00:42:14.720 --> 00:42:17.970
cut taxes and the 60s, when
John F. Kennedy cut taxes.

00:42:17.970 --> 00:42:21.070
Now we actually had a very
prosperous 80s and 90s period

00:42:21.070 --> 00:42:22.813
as well when Reagan cut
taxes, you could say,

00:42:22.813 --> 00:42:25.310
I know that you all,
'cause you work, you say,

00:42:25.310 --> 00:42:27.870
well, Clinton raised taxes but
we did all these other things

00:42:27.870 --> 00:42:29.920
We did welfare reform,
we did free trade deals,

00:42:29.920 --> 00:42:31.953
we did the capital gains tax cut, I mean,

00:42:31.953 --> 00:42:35.587
look, when you lower your
tax rates, you make America

00:42:35.587 --> 00:42:37.823
more competitive, you've
got to admit that point.

00:42:37.823 --> 00:42:40.310
I mean, countries do
compete, why do you think

00:42:40.310 --> 00:42:41.900
all these countries all
over the world have been

00:42:41.900 --> 00:42:44.580
cutting their corporate
tax rate for the last...

00:42:44.580 --> 00:42:45.890
- Well, that's actually,
you're proving my point

00:42:45.890 --> 00:42:47.640
because when we've cut
the corporate tax rate,

00:42:47.640 --> 00:42:49.170
what, do you think other countries are not

00:42:49.170 --> 00:42:50.560
gonna cut their tax rates?
- They probably will.

00:42:50.560 --> 00:42:52.520
- They're gonna do exactly what we do.

00:42:52.520 --> 00:42:55.969
That's exactly what this,
there's a race to the bottom.

00:42:55.969 --> 00:42:57.333
- But we didn't do it for 25 years,

00:42:57.333 --> 00:42:58.332
and the rest of the world

00:42:58.332 --> 00:42:59.380
so we had this massive gap,
the other thing we did,

00:42:59.380 --> 00:43:02.040
by the way, which I think
was wildly successful was

00:43:02.040 --> 00:43:05.280
we recognized that there was
something like three trillion

00:43:05.280 --> 00:43:08.777
dollars that was sitting
offshore in Bermuda, in China

00:43:08.777 --> 00:43:11.810
and Ireland and all
these countries that have

00:43:11.810 --> 00:43:15.010
lower tax rates than us, and
these companies like Boeing

00:43:15.010 --> 00:43:18.760
and General Electric and
Apple and Microsoft wanted

00:43:18.760 --> 00:43:20.370
to bring the money back but they couldn't

00:43:20.370 --> 00:43:21.750
'cause they faced a stiff penalty.

00:43:21.750 --> 00:43:24.230
So Trump, I don't know
why Obama didn't do this.

00:43:24.230 --> 00:43:26.810
The money was just lying
there, waiting to be picked up.

00:43:26.810 --> 00:43:30.090
We basically said, we'll charge
you 10%, you bring it back

00:43:30.090 --> 00:43:32.100
to the United States,
we think we're gonna get

00:43:32.100 --> 00:43:34.597
about two trillion dollars
back, that's $200 billion

00:43:34.597 --> 00:43:36.767
for the United States
government and it's two trillion

00:43:36.767 --> 00:43:38.000
dollars that's invested here, I mean,

00:43:38.000 --> 00:43:38.833
what's wrong with that?

00:43:38.833 --> 00:43:40.786
- In 2004, we did exactly the same thing,

00:43:40.786 --> 00:43:43.460
wait a minute, under the same promise,

00:43:43.460 --> 00:43:46.520
that it was all going to
lead to big, big investment

00:43:46.520 --> 00:43:48.620
and it was going to generate more jobs

00:43:48.620 --> 00:43:50.900
and higher wages and it didn't.

00:43:50.900 --> 00:43:52.975
We did the same experiment.
- We just had Apple bring

00:43:52.975 --> 00:43:55.930
$300 billion dollars back.

00:43:55.930 --> 00:43:58.010
I think this tax cut would
have been worth doing just

00:43:58.010 --> 00:43:59.940
to get Apple to bring all this money back.

00:43:59.940 --> 00:44:02.200
- Let me ask you a question
that comes from something

00:44:02.200 --> 00:44:04.050
one of the audience persons asked

00:44:04.050 --> 00:44:07.230
and that's this, suppose
you're right that in fact

00:44:07.230 --> 00:44:09.040
this is stimulating the
economy and that's great

00:44:09.040 --> 00:44:11.670
and jobs are coming back and so forth.

00:44:11.670 --> 00:44:13.911
If it is also, however,
going to make the rich richer

00:44:13.911 --> 00:44:18.260
and the fact is the tax
bill took the top tax rate,

00:44:18.260 --> 00:44:23.260
39.6 and made it 37% and
therefore that's one indication--

00:44:23.730 --> 00:44:25.671
- It's much more than
that for the wealthy.

00:44:25.671 --> 00:44:28.104
It did much more than
that for the wealthy.

00:44:28.104 --> 00:44:29.240
- Well, I'm just taking
one thing that it did

00:44:32.322 --> 00:44:33.550
that actually palpably
decreased tax rates on the rich.

00:44:33.550 --> 00:44:38.150
Is this the time, given what
Mr. Trump's political coalition

00:44:38.150 --> 00:44:41.170
is about, for us to be
going out and making

00:44:41.170 --> 00:44:45.180
the rich even richer, is
there a danger to democracy?

00:44:45.180 --> 00:44:48.060
Maybe we'll have a great
economy but a lousy democracy

00:44:48.060 --> 00:44:50.340
'cause we'll have a lot of
people out there who are really

00:44:50.340 --> 00:44:52.420
ready for revolution because
they feel like they've been

00:44:52.420 --> 00:44:55.770
so badly harmed and that
this is the new Gilded Age

00:44:55.770 --> 00:44:58.320
with lots of rich people
who are treating them badly?

00:44:58.320 --> 00:45:00.152
- And by the way, a lot of
those people are right here

00:45:00.152 --> 00:45:03.330
in Silicon Valley, I mean,
yeah, we do have Bill Gates

00:45:03.330 --> 00:45:07.060
who has $50 billion and we
have the people running Apple

00:45:07.060 --> 00:45:09.570
who have billions and we've
got Zuckerberg, who has $50

00:45:09.570 --> 00:45:10.830
billion, so what do you want to do?

00:45:10.830 --> 00:45:12.860
Would we be a better
country if we just deported

00:45:12.860 --> 00:45:15.210
all those people, I mean, I
just don't get this, look.

00:45:15.210 --> 00:45:19.100
I think you all obsess--
- No, no, I guess I'm saying,

00:45:19.100 --> 00:45:21.550
why did we decrease the tax rate from 39--

00:45:21.550 --> 00:45:23.093
- Because we wanted--
- To 37%.

00:45:23.093 --> 00:45:26.260
I know there's a technical
reason, but tell me,

00:45:26.260 --> 00:45:27.540
was that good politics?

00:45:27.540 --> 00:45:31.170
- Yes, I wanted the rate
down to, look, in 1986,

00:45:31.170 --> 00:45:33.000
to give you a sense of
how things have changed

00:45:33.000 --> 00:45:35.680
in this country, in 1986,
Ronald Reagan had a bill

00:45:35.680 --> 00:45:38.316
with Bill Bradley and
Dick Gebphard, Sam Nunn,

00:45:38.316 --> 00:45:41.960
many Democrats and we
basically lowered the tax rates

00:45:41.960 --> 00:45:45.040
and broadened, you know,
lowered the rates, broadened

00:45:45.040 --> 00:45:47.890
the base and that bill that
lowered the highest income tax

00:45:47.890 --> 00:45:49.500
rate, none of you are gonna
believe this, but you'll have

00:45:49.500 --> 00:45:52.580
to look it up, we got the
lowest tax rate down to 28%

00:45:52.580 --> 00:45:55.680
and that bill passed 97
to three in the Senate.

00:45:55.680 --> 00:45:57.230
Now we couldn't even get a single--

00:45:57.230 --> 00:45:58.442
- Wait a minute.

00:45:58.442 --> 00:45:59.880
- We couldn't get one
Democrat in the entire Senate

00:45:59.880 --> 00:46:02.563
to vote for a 37% tax rate.

00:46:02.563 --> 00:46:04.200
- Bob.

00:46:04.200 --> 00:46:06.788
- I thought that that '86
bill was a very good bill.

00:46:06.788 --> 00:46:07.621
- Me too.

00:46:07.621 --> 00:46:09.770
- And it also leveled
the playing field between

00:46:09.770 --> 00:46:12.137
capital gains and ordinary
income and that was one of

00:46:12.137 --> 00:46:14.402
the most important aspects of that bill.

00:46:14.402 --> 00:46:19.402
But you know, I'm reminded
here, Steve, of something else

00:46:20.500 --> 00:46:24.492
that we have debated almost
steadily for the past 30 years

00:46:24.492 --> 00:46:29.492
and that is the issue of
economic growth and what really

00:46:32.250 --> 00:46:36.921
stimulates economic growth,
I mean, in the 1950s,

00:46:36.921 --> 00:46:40.940
the highest marginal income tax was 91%

00:46:40.940 --> 00:46:44.410
and the effective rate
was 52% on individuals

00:46:44.410 --> 00:46:47.350
and we were growing faster
at an annual rate than we've

00:46:47.350 --> 00:46:49.218
ever grown before or since.

00:46:49.218 --> 00:46:52.550
You refer to the golden age of the 1920s.

00:46:52.550 --> 00:46:55.053
I don't want to live in
the 1920s even if I could.

00:46:55.053 --> 00:46:59.300
The 1920s was a period of extraordinary--

00:46:59.300 --> 00:47:00.510
- Wealth creation.

00:47:00.510 --> 00:47:02.522
- Wealth creation, inequality.

00:47:02.522 --> 00:47:03.786
- Yeah, the country got
rich, why do they think

00:47:03.786 --> 00:47:04.991
they call it the Roaring 20s?

00:47:04.991 --> 00:47:06.296
I mean--
- But it was also

00:47:06.296 --> 00:47:07.840
extraordinary inequality and corruption

00:47:08.781 --> 00:47:10.190
and it was kind of a period
of time that led ultimately

00:47:10.190 --> 00:47:13.070
to the great crash and
the Great Depression.

00:47:13.070 --> 00:47:15.382
Do you see any...

00:47:15.382 --> 00:47:20.343
Consequence between, in
1928 and 2007, the top 1%

00:47:23.130 --> 00:47:27.486
in both those years, 1928 and
2007, had the highest share

00:47:27.486 --> 00:47:30.840
of total national income
and we know what happened

00:47:30.840 --> 00:47:35.240
in the year after 2007 and 1928.

00:47:36.420 --> 00:47:38.060
Do you think there was any--

00:47:38.060 --> 00:47:42.862
- I mean, it is true, who are
these people in the top .001%?

00:47:42.862 --> 00:47:46.895
They're people, look, you could
take Bill Gates, Zuckerberg,

00:47:46.895 --> 00:47:51.895
who's the Amazon CEO, you
know, those five have...

00:47:53.290 --> 00:47:56.530
More money than most of
the countries in the world

00:47:56.530 --> 00:47:57.810
for goodness's sake so
what do you want to do,

00:47:57.810 --> 00:47:59.950
confiscate, take their
wealth away from them?

00:47:59.950 --> 00:48:02.770
Look, here's my problem with
the way you see the world

00:48:02.770 --> 00:48:05.190
versus the way I see it, I
want everybody to get rich,

00:48:05.190 --> 00:48:07.824
right, I don't care, I
want more millionaires

00:48:07.824 --> 00:48:09.796
and billionaires in this country.

